<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-243-257 </DOCNO><DOCID>09 755 219</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  Jan 14 1991 n1589* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Up-time guarantee wins switch computing a sturdy maintenancebusiness. (Switch Computing Ltd's successes in the computerindustry)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Switch computing Ltd. (Services).andO;Topic:     ForecastingMarketing StrategyUnited KingdomCustomer RelationsComputer Services.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>UP-TIME GUARANTEE WINS SWITCH COMPUTING A STURDYandM;MAINTENANCE BUSINESSandM;London's International Financial Futures Exchange has joined the seven-strongclient list of a small computer maintenance company established in 1989 byLee Allwood, formerly with Granada Computer Services.andP;  Over the past 16months, Allwood has recruited a further three directors, all from theComputer Field Maintenance arm of Granada Group Plc, and Switch Computing Ltdis now boasting that without the aid of institutional investors, it is ontarget to achieve #1m turnover by April, with net profits around 15%.andP;  Switchhas a headcount of 15, including 11 engineers, and is targeting the City andLondon as its primary market.andP;  Simon Burton, Switch's sales and marketingdirector, says that the company will either maintain equipment using itsin-house skills, or subcontract back to the manufacturer.andP;  Burton believesthat this enables the client to have one point of contact only, and it alsomeans that Switch can offer installation-wide maintenance.andP;  The company iskeen to draw a distinction between guaranteed response time offered by anumber of maintenance companies and the guaranteed availability time thatSwitch includes in its contracts.andP;  Burton acknowledges that customers willpay for this service, but he argues that a two hour response time ismeaningless if the subsequent repairs and maintenance take so long that theyseriously affect a customer's productivity.andO;</TEXT></DOC>